        "user": "How does \"gradient descent\" differ from simulated annealing?",
        "assistant": "# Gradient Descent vs. Simulated Annealing\n\nThese two algorithms represent fundamentally different philosophies of optimization. Gradient descent is **deterministic and greedy**; simulated annealing is **stochastic and exploratory**.\n\n## The Core Difference\n\n- **Gradient descent** uses *calculus* — it follows the slope downhill.\n- **Simulated annealing** uses *randomness* — it makes random moves and sometimes accepts *worse* solutions on purpose.\n\nThe big consequence: gradient descent gets stuck in local minima; simulated annealing is designed to escape them.\n\n## How Each Works\n\n### Gradient Descent\n1. Compute gradient $\\nabla f(\\theta)$\n2. Step in the direction of steepest descent\n3. Repeat until convergence\n\n$$\\theta_{new} = \\theta_{old} - \\alpha \\cdot \\nabla f(\\theta)$$\n\nAlways moves **downhill** (assuming reasonable learning rate).\n\n### Simulated Annealing\n1. Start at some point with a high \"temperature\" $T$\n2. Propose a **random neighbor** $\\theta'$\n3. Compute change in cost: $\\Delta f = f(\\theta') - f(\\theta)$\n4. Accept the new point with probability:\n\n$$P(\\text{accept}) = \\begin{cases} 1 & \\text{if } \\Delta f < 0 \\;(\\text{better}) \\\\ e^{-\\Delta f / T} & \\text{if } \\Delta f \\geq 0 \\;(\\text{worse}) \\end{cases}$$\n\n5. Gradually **cool** $T$ over time\n6. Repeat\n\nCrucially, it can move **uphill** — and is more likely to do so when $T$ is high.\n\n## The Annealing Metaphor\n\nThe name comes from metallurgy: heating a metal and slowly cooling it lets atoms settle into a low-energy crystalline structure. Cool too fast → defects (local minima). Cool slowly → near-optimal structure (global minimum).\n\n- **High $T$**: Algorithm wanders freely, accepts almost anything → broad exploration\n- **Low $T$**: Algorithm becomes picky, mostly downhill → fine-tuning\n- **$T \\to 0$**: Behaves like a random local search (greedy)\n\n## Side-by-Side Comparison\n\n| Aspect | Gradient Descent | Simulated Annealing |\n|--------|------------------|---------------------|\n| **Approach** | Deterministic, calculus-based | Stochastic, sampling-based |\n| **Requires gradient?** | Yes | No ✓ |\n| **Function must be differentiable?** | Yes | No ✓ |\n| **Accepts worse moves?** | Never | Yes (probabilistically) |\n| **Escapes local minima?** | No (gets stuck) | Yes ✓ |\n| **Finds global minimum?** | Only if convex | Theoretically yes (with slow enough cooling) |\n| **Convergence speed** | Fast (when it works) | Slow |\n| **Hyperparameters** | Learning rate | Initial temp, cooling schedule, neighbor function |\n| **Scales to millions of params?** | Yes ✓ | Poorly |\n| **Best for** | Smooth, continuous problems | Combinatorial, non-smooth, multi-modal problems |\n\n## A Visual Intuition\n\nImagine a landscape with multiple valleys:\n\n```\n          GD gets stuck here ↓\n                ___           \n               /   \\      ___        ← global minimum\n   _____     /     \\    /   \\    /\n        \\___/       \\__/     \\__/\n              ↑\n         SA can escape this valley\n         by occasionally jumping uphill\n```\n\nGradient descent only flows downhill — once in a basin, it stays. Simulated annealing can hop over ridges, especially early on.\n\n## When to Use Which\n\n### Use Gradient Descent when:\n- Function is **differentiable** (or sub-differentiable)\n- Problem is **continuous** and reasonably smooth\n- You have **many parameters** (deep learning, regression)\n- Speed matters and local minima aren't catastrophic\n\n### Use Simulated Annealing when:\n- Function is **non-differentiable**, noisy, or a **black box**\n- Search space is **discrete or combinatorial** (e.g., scheduling, routing)\n- The landscape has **many local minima**\n- You can afford slow convergence to find a global optimum\n\n## Classic Application Domains\n\n| Gradient Descent | Simulated Annealing |\n|------------------|---------------------|\n| Neural networks | Traveling Salesman Problem |\n| Linear/logistic regression | VLSI chip layout |\n| Matrix factorization | Protein folding |\n| Differentiable physics | Job scheduling |\n| Image reconstruction | Graph coloring |\n\n## Hybrid Approaches\n\nIn practice, the line blurs:\n- **SGD's noise** acts a bit like a mild form of annealing — random kicks help escape shallow minima\n- **Learning rate schedules** that decrease over time mirror cooling schedules\n- **Stochastic Gradient Langevin Dynamics (SGLD)** explicitly adds Gaussian noise to gradient updates, blending the two paradigms\n- **Basin hopping**: alternates random jumps with local gradient-based optimization\n\n## A Key Theoretical Result\n\nSimulated annealing has a remarkable guarantee: with a **sufficiently slow logarithmic cooling schedule** ($T_k \\propto 1/\\log k$), it converges to the **global minimum with probability 1**.\n\nThe catch? \"Sufficiently slow\" is so slow that in practice you use faster (e.g., geometric) cooling schedules and accept that you might miss the true global optimum.\n\n## Summary\n\nGradient descent is a **mountaineer with a compass** — efficient, directed, but easily trapped in valleys. Simulated annealing is a **drunken hiker who slowly sobers up** — initially wandering everywhere, gradually settling into the deepest valley it can find.\n\nThey're complementary tools: gradient descent dominates continuous, differentiable, large-scale problems (like deep learning), while simulated annealing shines in discrete, rugged, or black-box landscapes where calculus simply doesn't apply.\n\nWant me to dive into **other gradient-free optimizers** (genetic algorithms, particle swarm, Bayesian optimization), or explore how **noise-injected gradient methods** like SGLD bridge these two worlds?",
